_js\";a:5:{s:5:\"#type\";s:8:\"textarea\";s:5:\"#rows\";i:10;s:7:\"#teaser\";s:9:\"edit-body\";s:16:\"#teaser_checkbox\";s:19:\"edit-teaser-include\";s:9:\"#disabled\";b:1;}s:14:\"teaser_include\";a:5:{s:5:\"#type\";s:8:\"checkbox\";s:6:\"#title\";s:25:\"Show summary in full view\";s:14:\"#default_value\";b:1;s:7:\"#prefix\";s:29:\"<div class=\"teaser-checkbox\">\";s:7:\"#suffix\";s:6:\"</div>\";}s:4:\"body\";a:5:{s:5:\"#type\";s:8:\"textarea\";s:6:\"#title\";s:4:\"Body\";s:14:\"#default_value\";s:1143:\"<p>\r\n	Nuno Godinho has developed a very interessting software in [[VVVV]] that plays with video-time in relation to what is show in the image.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Taking a video of a director he tracked the tip of his baton throughout the video. This produced a point cloud representing all possible positions that the tip has taken in regard to the video frame. For each point / pixel on the video frame he could find the closest position that the tip ever took throughout the video allowing him to position the tip in the image. He calls this <strong>&quot;fake inverse kinematics&quot;.</strong> Based on paths drawn on the video he was able to generate a new video in which the tip of the baton would follow this path (see below), or as he writes: <em>&quot;directing the director&quot;.</em></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<iframe frameborder=\"0\" height=\"320\" src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/9754197?title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0&amp;color=ffffff\" width=\"400\"></iframe></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Original footage can be seen here:&nbsp;<br />\r\n	http://vimeo.com/7772145&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Nunos project page is here:<br />\r\n	http://projects.nunogodinho.com/2010/maestro</p>\r\n\";s:5:\"#rows\";i:20;s:9:\"#required\";b:0;}s:6:\"format\";a:13:{s:5:\"#type\";s:8:\"fieldset\";s:6:\"#title\";s:12:\"Input format\";s:12:\"#collapsible\";b:1;s:10:\"#collapsed\";b:1;s:7:\"#weight\";N;s:17:\"#element_validate\";a:1:{i:0;s:20:\"filter_form_validate\";}i:1;a:7:{s:5:\"#type\";s:5:\"radio\";s:6:\"#ti